Introduction¶

The current dataset was obtained from Kaggle, it represents more than one hundred thousand entries for medical appointments in Brazil. The dataset contains information regarding the patient's ID, appointment date and time, hospital location, whether the patient is enrolled in the Brazilian welfare program Bolsa Familia, chronic diseases the patient has, and whether or not the patient showed up to their appointment.

The report focuses on the prevalence of not showing up for medical appointments in Brazil, according to the included data set, and factors that are key predictors for patients to show up or not for their medical appointments.

Research Questions¶

Depending on the primary exploration and visualization of data, a few questions were suggested for the purpose of generating the current investigative report. Questions are as follows:

  1. Are scheduling or appointment time or date a determinant for not showing up for appointments in Brazil?
  2. Are socio-demographic characteristics a determinant for not showing up for appointments in Brazil?
  3. Are medical history a determinant for not showing up for appointments in Brazil?
  4. Is receiving a reminder SMS for appointments a determinant for showing up for appointments in Brazil?
  5. Is there a comination of factors cosidered a stronf determinant for not showing up for appointments in Brazil?

data_list = ['PatientId', 'Gender', 'ScheduledDay',
             'AppointmentDay', 'Age', 'Neighbourhood',
             'Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes',
             'Alcoholism', 'Handcap', 'SMS_received', 'No-show']

# Checking for individual duplicated entries in data frame without the AppointmentID column.
df.duplicated(data_list).sum()
Out[6]:
618

The data set shows 618 duplicated entries. After removing the AppointmentID column, it appears that there are 618 duplicated entries with identical data for PatientID, ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay that could be one of two things; 1) either it's a system glitch, booking the same appointment for the same patient in the exact same time (but with different consequent Appointment ID), or 2) the patient has booked two different services on the exact same time on a single appointment (like booking two different clinics at the same time, or booking an extra laboratory or pharmacy appointment ... etc.).

Knowing that this information is not currently available and possibly hard to find, all entries for the current data set will be preserved for the purpose of the current investigative report (as each entry has a unique AppointmentID).

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Data frame will be treated for each column at a time, descriptive data for gathering frequencies regarding specific item like age, gender ... etc. with the affiliated plots, then another plot and description will be generated for that specific item and its relation with the not showing up for the appointments. Later in the report, a cross relation will be considered for data frame items and not showing up for appointments to identify a possible relation.

# Creating functions for showing figures.
def counts_figure(df, x, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize= (15, 5))
    sns.countplot(data = df, x = x, color = None, palette= None)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)

def relation_figure(df, x, hue, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize= (15, 5))
    sns.countplot(data = df, x = x, hue = hue)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

In [31]:
# Displaying independent smaples test relationship results 
# between gender and now show data for appointments data. 
group1 = df[df['Gender'] == "M"]
group2 = df[df['Gender'] == "F"]

ttest, pvalue = ttest_ind(group1['no_show'], group2['no_show'])
print('Independet samples t test = {}, significance (p value) = {}'
      .format(round(ttest, 3), round(pvalue, 3)))

Independet samples t test = -1.37, significance (p value) = 0.171

Data frame shows that females not showing for their appointments more than males, with 20.31% of female patients have not showed up for their appointments, while 19.97% of male patients haven't showed up for their appointments. The mean change for not showing up for appointments was not statistically signigicantly between males and females (t= 1.370, p= 0.171).

Data frame shows a moderate positive statistical correlation between age, hypertension (r= 0.5), and diabetes (r= 0.28), indicating an increase in hypertension and diabetes frequency with aging, and an increased diabetes frequency with hypertension (r= 0.42). Not showing for appointments had a weak negative statistical correlation with age (r= -0.1).

Conclusions¶

Research Questions answered:¶

Regarding scheduling or appointment time or date, scheduling an appointment in March, Friday or 9:00 PM had the highest chance of not showing up for appointments, while the appointment being in May or Saturday had the highest chance of not showing up for appointments.

In regards to socio-demographic characteristics, female centenarians, male adolescents, SANTOS DUMONT neighbourhood, no subscription to the Brazilian welfare program "Bolsa Familia", not having hypertension or diabetes, and patients with disabilities have the highest chance of not showing up for appointments. In addition, receiving a reminder SMS decreased the number of not showing up for appointments in none same-day and on-spot reservations.

Final Conclusion¶

In conclusion, there is a 20% chance of not showing up for a scheduled appointment, almost a 29% chance of not showing up if the scheduling day is not the same as the appointment day. Data shows a slight effect from indicators for not showing up for appointments (like age, chronic diseases, and receiving a reminder SMS) however, its impact on a decision can't be established, which requires new parameters or more complete and accurate data entries for the current dataset. Dependent and Independent variables statistically correlate with a weak to moderarte correlation.
